title: Hexagonal game tile bases and cutters

description.text:
Someone I know is hand-making a game that uses hexagonal pieces. They are using epoxy modelling clay and other miniature figure making materials. When I saw they were cutting the bases by hand I offered to print simple plastic bases for them or make a convenient hexagon "cookie-cutter" so that they would line up with each other better. These pieces are 33mm along a side or 66mm from two opposite points... so they are smaller than Catan pieces (which are 45mm on a side and 90mm across BTW), however as the script is parametric it could be modified to make compatible tiles. Changes from previous versions:
0.3
  • Added proper comments and cleaned up code
  • Implemented Parametric Variables
    0.2
  • switched to using 6 sided conical frustrum
    0.1
  • First attempt using extruded 6-sided polygon

• Decide on size of your pieces and modify .scad variables to suit, make sure to choose if you want a base or cutter using the is_base variables and enter your printers layer_height if you want a hollow base
  • Save, generate shape and export .stl
  • Print as many bases as you will need pieces or just a few cutters and cleanup rough edges
  • Cut your modelling material with the cutter or smoosh it into the hollow bases
  • Make 'em pretty
  • Play!

description.text:
A remix of the @alga42's design of a 58mm Espresso Tamper. This is a 50mm version, with a few changes to it and its holder as well.

I made the grip a bit oblong. not visually noticeable but IMHO it fits nicer into a human hand when it's slightly oval. Result feels good.

Changed the tamper end to 50mm, so it fits into a Salton-brand (not-so–fancy-but-serviceable) espresso maker. (EX-96)

Made the base a bit thicker.

I've removed a big chunk of material from the interior of the handle. And even at 25% fill, it still feels very solid, so that worked well and saves much filament.

Note there's a file for just the tamper and another for the tamper plus the modified holder unit. I haven't tried to print the holder, but it should work. Let me know if you try it! I adjusted the entry-point for the tamper, as it looked a little shallow in the original design, and I worried it might flop out of the holder. Given the nice colour match to my unit, I'm happy to just sit the tamper on top (see the picture).

A fun idea - as it was building, I realized I could throw a few coffee beans into the cavity in the handle, and they would rattle pleasantly when I shook it, yet not be removable without a hammer or drill. Fun stuff. (see pic).

An added bonus, the white PLA filament (Monoprice) I used is a near perfect colour match for the Salton unit, so it looks nice sitting on top.

title: Xbox One Elite Controller Battery Cover For Energizer Recharge Battery

description.text:
EDIT: I added a file that includes supports which can be printed well on an Ultimaker 2. When you place the part in Cura, just rotate it 180 degrees to orient the supports properly.

This is a battery pack cover for Xbox One elite controllers. It was designed to be compatible with the Energizer Charging System. The charge can be found here:

https://www.amazon.com/Microsoft-licensed-Energizer-Charging-System-Xbox/dp/B00EADTVLW/

This charging system is not compatible with Elite controllers as they have a different orientation for the lock pins, so I designed a back that is compatible. I used the Xbox One Controller Battery Cover by Stephen_J as a template.

Can be printed on: FormLabs Form 1, MakerBot Replicator 2.

Enjoy!

Notes:

I have printed this on a FormLabs Form 1 printer by using the automatic Support Generation. I also printed it on a MakerBot Replicator 2 with just a raft, however the quality wasn't as impressive. However, I did notice that the MakerBot's print worked much better when used in the controller. I have also tried printing it on an Ultimaker 2, however I have had more difficulty with using that machine as the piece is rather thin. I will do more tests and post the results here.

When printed on the MakerBot, the overhanging parts have some slight distortion. I simply cut the frayed bits off with an x-acto knife, and it still works fine. It is also possible to use the built in support function for the MakerBot, however the supports can be very difficult to remove.

I will post more images later.

The printing setup in PreForm. Dark picture showing the controller charging with the battery cover on.

To design this part I used the Xbox One Controller Battery Cover by Stephen_J as a template. Then I made some rough measurements of the different features of the battery cover that comes with the Energizer Charging Stand, and made a rough design. I then printed the part a couple times and tried it out, and made adjustments where they were necessary. The main difficulty came from the two bars on the inside as they needed to be oriented really precisely to fit in the slots on the battery pack.

title: Camera mount for Sweex USB camera on Vertex K8400

description.text:
An assembly to use my Sweex USB web camera with the Vertex K8400 3D printer.

Initially, I had intended to use only the camera mount & the base components - turned out the camera was way to close to the printer and I'd only be able to see the center area of the build. Not good enough... :-)

Added a set of 3 arms, which gives the camera a nice range of adjustability - now I can make any angle I need. Drawback was, that with this height, the narrow base turned out to be insufficiently stable. Right.

Solved that, by adding a sort of a dock for the base - which seems to have solved the issues: it's working quite alright, now.

Now there's only 1 thing left to do... sort out the lighting...
I'm currently printing with white PLA and with that very white material sitting on the thoroughly black build plate, that's a bit too much contrast for the Sweex to handle.

Never a dull day... :-)

description.text:
I wanted a more traditional and accurate representations of the Fisher Price Cash Register coins (model #B926A) and was able to use one of the original coins as a starting point.

Would love if someone would add the bumps to the inside coin surface.

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

No

No

Resolution:

Fast

Infill:

The Story of How

My in-laws had an old vintage Fisher Price Cash Register sitting in their basement and my 5 and 7 year old immediately took to it, the problem was that there were only two coins left.

I was already thinking about how to set up a coin-bank for the 3D printer at school and so I asked if she might lend me toy. She gave it to me instead.

I got home and found this helpful resource:
http://www.thisoldtoy.com/l_fp_set/toy-pages/900-999/926-cashregister.html

From here I was able to back calculate exact dimensions for the coins and in Tinkercad was able to make a reasonable facsimile that looked and felt more consistent with the original toy than could be found in the Thingiverse database.

I wanted to make sure that the lines were smooth so I elected the three-piece design that would snap together in the end. First prototype came off really well, but wasn't aesthetically perfect so I increased the font slightly, and made the middle notch of the ring much more pronounced. I haven't tried 10 and 5 yet (only built 25 before writing this up) but I think it should all work well.

All in all - for all three coins it took about 3 hours to create start to finish, and another 5 hours of printing to get them all into the real-world!

Here's the actual machine we have at work!

My Rostock is being used as a demonstrator of 3d printing for several events where small children and adults want stick their hands into the printer. So, I made an enclosure that will use 12x24" sheets of 1/4" Acrylic. This also will cut down on drafts and prevent warping of large parts.  
I have not oriented anything, you will have rotate the part so that you can print them. If you cant do this, you probably should learn before you attempt building this!  
Coming soon; door handle and locking latch!  
I used some bearings I had laying around for this. They measure 1.125" OD 0.5" ID and 0.375" thick. I may modify this for use with a more common skate board bearing in the future.

This will require
3ea 12x24" 1/4" thick acrylic in your choice of color
20ea 1/4-20x1" bolts
20 ea 1/4-20 nuts
40ea 1/4" flat washers
2 bearings that I listed in the description. Print
2 enclosure bracket
2 enclosure bracket (mirrored)
4 enclosure bottom bracket
2 Door bearing
1 bottomdoor.STL
1 topdoorbearing.STL Place 1 Enclosure bracket and 1 enclosure bracket(mirrored) onto the top of the acrylic, flush with the edge. Mark and drill 1/4" holes into the acylic. Locate 2 of the enclosure bottom brackets and dry fit them onto the bottom of the acrylic sheet and position the assembly onto your Rostock Max. Take some time to check clearances between the skate and the acrylic and make sure everything is centered. Mark and drill holes to mount the enclosure brackets to the top of the printer. Now we are going to position the bottom brackets, fix them to the base and bolt them to the acrylic. With the enclosure brackets bolted to the acylic and the top of the printer position the enclosure bottom brackets so they look nice and are not covering up any screws or important holes. Take some masking tape and mask around the bottom to mark the position and protect the melamine. Mix up some epoxy and glue the enclosure bottom brackets into position. Once the epoxy has cured mark and drill the holes to bolt the acrylic to the enclosure bottom brackets. Coming soon, mounting the door!

Notes:

I printed mine with a raft, no supports, .2mm layer height, 215C PLA, and 15% infill.

I used a 15% infill because the difference in plastic used and print time were minimal, but a 10% infill would likely be more than enough. The undersides of the question marks drooped a little without supports, but not enough to really notice. I also printed this with a raft, but I don't think it would make a difference.

When designing this block I tried to match the original Mario question block design as close as possible. In Solidworks, I started with a perfect cube, created one side with a protruding question mark and four circles, beveled all of the edges, and then copied it to the remaining three sides. The print may appear to be uneven because the x and y are equal while the z measurement is shorter, but this is simply because the top and bottom of the cube are flat (do not contain protruding question marks) while the other four sides are not.

I'm back with another 3D design for you, and this time we're making the Planet Express Ship! As a long time fan of Futurama, I'm really excited about this model. I broke it up into a few pieces so it's easier to print. But unfortunately that makes it pretty hard to scale. I would say scaling down much won't be possible due to the size of some of the details, but scaling up should be okay, you might just need to adjust the pin sizes to fit the tolerances better.

I modeled this in Fusion 360 (link: http://autode.sk/1s0ABZA) using the sculpting and sketch tools available there. Then I sliced it in Simplify3D (settings below) and printed it out on my Robo3D R1. I used white Hatchbox PLA. Then my wife sanded, glued and painted the entire thing using an airbrush and paintbrushes.

description.text:
I wanted to make a slider you can Print that will work on almost all types of 20x20 Aluminium profiles. It uses 4mm PTFE bowden tubing as the material in contact with the aluminum profile. It makes contact in 8 places (4 on each end).
The screws at the end adjust the pressure of the bowden tubes against the profile, by using ramps.
You have to adjust the screws to find a compromise between a wiggle free slider and friction.
The nature of the design requires pieces of bowden tubing of equal length and benefit from a tube with a V-Cutout at the end. I have included a part for trimming the tube using a sharp tool, for example a wood chisel.
To make sure the Part in the core doesn't move compared to the outer part, I used some bowden Tubing mounted in groves. This isn't needed for the entire length, just some in the back and some in the front.

I might use this for a z-axis as it might have to much friction for a x or y-axis.
Also it should shed some weight for using it as a x- or y-axis

It needs only a little bit of hardware to assemble.
I used:
4x 6mm M3 screws
4x M3 brass inserts
2x 30mm M3 screws
2x M3 nuts
and around 1/2 m of 4mm bowden tubing

description.text:
After replacing the rattling linear ball bearings with silent bearings from igus, I noticed they had less play and the carriage was a little harder to move. Unfortunately, the motion system of the printer is as bad as everything on this printer, so each time the direction reversed, the additional friction made the print bed turn a little. Ruined my prints because parallel lines with the same distance didn't come out at the same distance if they were printed in reverse directions. Especially visible on bottom and top infill.

This thing fixes the problem by putting the bearings for X-motion wider apart, so the carriage cannot do this turning motion anymore.

Supports:

Yes

Notes:

This design needs supports to get the "wings" right. The supported plane is the one the bearing holders will be screwed onto, so they don't need to be super-pretty. But they do need to be flat.

comments.text:
Hi,
I had the same sort of issue with these bearings and I resolved not using the seeger retaining rings. They are too strong and deform the bearings, applying extra friction.
Instead the seeger retaining rings, I've used some simpler C retaing rings (or a simple steel wire, C shaped), less strong but them do not allow the bearing to escacpe from the supports.
With this solution, the plastic bearings are far more smooth and quiter than classical ones.

The objective of this project is to introduce your students to botany and hydroponics. Your students will also learn about capillary action. Lesson:

After you have printed the self-watering planter for your students you are going to demonstrate how it works. Fill the bottom piece about halfway with water. Fill the top piece with soil, plant the seeds, and water the soil. Place the planters by the window sill and let the seeds do their work! The plant seeds you choose are also up to you. Remember to check the water levels every few days.

How students are graded is up to the instructor. I recommend grading them on the health of their plant plus a quiz on what they were taught.

This is a replica of the top plate of the 2016 FlashForge Creator Pro (unsure whether this is different on older models). This is the part that connects the umbilical cord and the filament guide tubes to the carriage. Some possible reasons why you could want to download and print this:

  • You want to pimp an older Creator Pro to be more similar to the 2016 model,
  • You somehow destroyed the original during one of your wild experiments (how you're going to print this with your broken printer, well that's your problem),
  • You want to modify it to attach other things,
  • You want to print a lightweight replica to reduce the weight of the printing head in an attempt to reduce ringing,
  • You want to fill it with sand in an attempt to reduce ringing.

Two versions are included: one with normal round holes, and one with polyholes that should give a better chance at properly dimensioned holes without post-processing. If the holes come out too small anyway, use a 3 mm drill for the screw holes and wiggle a 6 mm drill around in the tube holes, which should be about 6.2 mm diameter.

This part does not have very stringent requirements when it comes to structural integrity, as its only real task is to hold the umbilical and filament guide tubes in place. This means only the zone around the holes is important. Use at least 3 shells and sufficient bottom and top layers to ensure the holes are up to the task.
Use a material that can withstand at least some heat, as the steppers can get quite hot. ABS is fine, PLA not really (and is heavy to boot, so a bad choice for weight loss if that's you goal). I have been using the ABS printed version shown in the photo for many months, and it doesn't exhibit any deformation at all.

I printed it for weight reduction, even though my printed part only removes 12 grams compared to the solid original which weighs about 22.8 g. Still, together with other tweaks, I removed 21 grams in total, and a comparison does show the ringing oscillation to die out slightly quicker. I obtained a better reduction in ringing by simply adding a paperclip tensioner to the X axis belt, and by far the largest improvement is by removing the unused stepper motor when not using it for single-extrusion prints (which account for about 95% of all my prints).

I'm not sure if the sand idea has any merit. Some say that attaching a sand-filled box could help in dampening oscillations, others say it will only make it worse. Anyone who has the time to try this, I'm interested in the results. I would use a 15% honeycomb infill and pause the print right before the top layers start printing, then carefully pour sand into the honeycombs until they are filled to about 50%, and resume the print. I guess the theory is that the energy surplus from sudden decelerations will be partly dissipated by the random motion of sand grains bouncing around, but only an experiment could show whether this has any… grain of truth in it :p

description.text:
Another Update:
Sorry to everyone who's already downloaded this. I've exported some parts in the lower frame part which will make inserting the leds almost impossible. The fixed version has been uploaded.

Update:
Added bottom, front and clip for the center. While there's not enough space for an Arduino Uno due to the way I've built it, there's plenty of room for Arduino nano/micro and
some other stuff (like an IR-receiver for example).

Print Center_Bottom, fix it with 3 screws (I used M3x12), put on Center_Front and slide the clip on the backside, pictures will follow.

And another go at something I had lying around for a very long time. This star is made out of 5 pieces which can be put together using glue or (which I prefer) M3x6 screws and nuts.

The star will be almost 17 inches in size after putting together the 5 frame parts. They can be printed on a 150mm x 150mm surface when rotated by 45 degrees. They are 167mm x 108mm.

Afterwards a led strip can be put in, when using strips with 30 leds/m they should fit nice and evenly in there. I haven't tried using waterproof strips, they might be a tad to thick. I went the arduino way to make them light, but I don't see any reason why one should not fit one of those ready-2-use led strips with an ir remote control...

As always there's one thing missing - something to cover up the middle of the star. Still not sure what to do, if I'm gonna fit the arduino inside the star or just put a wire down to whatever... ;)

The parts have tolerances in the range of 0.2mm - 0.4mm. The top parts should clip on and hold strong enough - if not you might heat the inner lips up and bend them outwards slightly.

The inner frames can be used in different ways, so I've put 3 of them here. I ended up printing v2 with clear pla and a 25% infill rotated by 30 degrees on every angle. That gave a nice effect and good diffusion. I also printed the caps without a solid bottom. I'm printing on glass and don't really like the glossy finish on big surfaces.

The last picture is inner frame v1 printed in black pla with a sheet of paper on top.

Basic Mounting Instructions

Screw the pieces together using M3x6 screws. Or glue them together. Or talk to them until they bond to each other.

This example is for a strip with 30 leds/m using WS2812 controllers:
We will be using 9 leds/frame, so a total of 45 leds is needed. Have a closer look at the strip - at some points the pads between the leds will be soldered and you do not want this to be the point which gets bended: between the frames. So make sure between every 9 leds there's clean pads which won't get harmed when bended.

Put the strip inside the frame parts, do not glue them on yet.

Screwed together using M3x6 screws and nuts. The hole size for the led strip is 11,5mm x 2,5mm Make sure everything looks okay before using the adhesive tape Basic wiring

First of all: There's quite a lot of great tutorials and guides on using led strips with an arduino. I suggest having a look at FastLED and/or the comprehensive Adafruit NeoPixels ÜberGuide from Adafruit. This is not really the place to get deep into WS2812 topics, there's really good information already out there :)

And remember: Those leds can draw quite a lot of power. 45 of them at full brightness/white will be using 2.7A. So do not try to power this from a usb port or from the +5V port on the arduino.

I am using a stabilized 5V power supply with 8A. This is way more than needed but at the moment this all is just "experimental playground" - so I'm using what I have at home.

PSU +5V -> LED strip +5V
PSU GND -> LED strip GND
PSU GND -> Arduino GND
Arduino IO Port 6 -> 300-500 ohm resistor -> LED strip DIN (watch the arrows)

The arduino will be powered by usb. Later on the PSU +5V can be connected to the Arduino +5V pin - but you should avoid this when having it connected to usb. And the psu should deliver +5V, not +4V or +6V...

According to the library you're going to use you might use another IO Port for connecting the data line. But there's plenty of information about that just where you got the library from. ;)

remixed_from.author: Martijndewinter
remixed_from.title: IKEA Dioder clamps for Ultimaker Original

description.text:
Looking for a way to mount the dioder LED strips of Ikea inside my Ultimaker Original, I came across the design of Martijndewinter. When printed, I noticed that the small notches of the clamps where not properly designed for some of the 4 clamps, actually they where not attached to the main part. Next to that, I was not very satisfied with the way I had to mount the LED strips on the Ultimaker.
So, based on Martijn's design, I created 2 new clamps. One to mount the dioder strip on the left and right top side (this is different from other designs I found on Thingiverse), and one to mount the strip inside the left and right corner of the front panel (which is an improved version of Martijn's design).
There is one drawback: the top lights are partly shaded by the belt. However, due to the different angles of the 4 led strips, you will still have plenty of light on the print in progress.

The top strips will just fit in, you have to fumble the connecting cable a bit to let it run free of the axes. The side strips are easier, as there is more space for the strips.

The connection cables which are supplied with the dioder strips are too short for this construction, so you have to desolder the plugs and put some slightly longer cables to the plugs (about 50% longer should be sufficient). The cable is difficult to get out, you have to flip the notch in the plug up.

So, the top and front strips are interconnected at both sides. The power cables can be lead to the existing holes in the bottom plate. The white dioder has a connection box to connect up to 4 strips. The main power lead is guided along the main board. The power switch of the dioder set is not mounted to the Ultimaker, but you can do that if you want to.

The top clamps are attached using 10mm bolts. The holes are 80mm from the back and the front of the top panel, and 7mm from the inside edge.

The side clamps are attached using 10mm bolts. The holes are drilled 80mm from the top, and 120mm from the bottom of the front panel, and 22mm from the side panel (use the inside edge to measure from, measuring from the curved side is very difficult :-) )

When drilling, make sure you have a piece of plywood below the hole to be drilled (just a small leftover of the panels will do fine). Not only will it prevent splintering, but it will also avoid drilling through the belt.....

description.header: Connecting the dioder strips to the main board
description.text:
If you want to, you can use the dioder connectors to connect to the Utlimaker Original+ main board, Ikea has (luckily) used the same plug for this on the white version of the main board. It will take some soldering and you have to connect each set of the strips in a serial way, as the Original+ supplies 24V and the dioder strips are 12V. Next to that you have to create custom firmware to be able to switch on the lights. See https://ultimaker.com/en/community/8807-main-links-for-marlin-firmware for more information on this.
The Ultimaker Original (so not the +) is supplying 12v, but I have no proper knowledge on connecting led strips to that main board.

You will also need:
4 10x3mm bolts (top left and right)
4 14x3mm bolts (front left and right)
8 hex nuts
3mm drill

title: Various filament guides for the Geeetech Acrylic Prusa i3

description.text:
The edges of the display board of the Geetech acrylic Prusa i3 are rather sharp and filament fed from behind the printer tends to rub against them or even get pulled in the corner the display board and teh main upper bridge forms.

So I designed a few things that are supposed to make the filament run over that edge more smoothly.

The objects are supposed to be clipped to the top of the display board, thus the 5mm slot.

author: datdiy

description.text:
The guys at Moving Brands challenged us to help them print their own Chocolate Advent Calendar in a month. We already knew about the Frostruder, and had most of the parts to build a RepRap Prusa, so the solution seemed obvious. They ordered a Frostruder, and we got busy building their Prusa. Things got exciting when we tried to mount the Frostruder to the Prusa carriage - it was just too big and bulky! Luckily, inspiration struck. We stripped down the Frostruder to the bare bones, and used the Prusa to print its own adaptor. Lo and behold, chocolate printing goodness! Moving Brands Advent Promotional Video: http://vimeo.com/33775105
Moving Brands Advent Calendar: http://www.movingbrands.com/advent

• Print the syringe adaptor. The attached STL is compatible with the Greg Frost LM8UU X carriage (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:9869). Edit the SCAD file parameters for other carriages.

  • Assemble the Frostruder according to the following steps in the instructions http://wiki.makerbot.com/frostruder-mk2-assembly (ignore the others):
    a. Prep Work - Port Orientation
    b. Prep Work - Connector Installation
    c. Prep Work (optional) - paint/seal wood
    d. Attach Valves to Syringe Bottom
    e. Cut Tubes to Length
    f. Attach Tubes to Tee
    g. Attach Tubes to Solenoids
    h. Cut More Tubing
    i. Insert Tube into Stopper
    j. Apply Clamps
    k. Attach Syringe Tube to Tee
    l. Attach Tubes to Input/Output

  • Mount the syringe on the X carriage using the adaptor and some M4 bolts (M4x16 or longer should do it) and nuts. Squeeze the two halves of the clamp together when tightening to get a firm grip on the syringe.

  • Mount the Syringe Bottom plate on the M8 threaded rod at the top of the frame use M8 nuts.

  • Hook up the solenoid valves to your electronics, and adjust your firmware to power on and off the valves in response to the appropriate GCode commands:
    M106 - pressure valve on (commonly Fan on)
    M107 - pressure valve off (commonly Fan off)
    M126 - relief valve on
    M127 - relief valve off
    • If your electronics and firmware are set up to use a fan, it is usually sufficient to hook the pressure solenoid up in place of the fan. The relief valve takes a little more work, as it often requires appropriating either the extruder heater or heated bed connections.

  • Attach your compressed air source.

  • Get printing! http://wiki.makerbot.com/frostruder-mk2-usage
    • For chocolate, you may wish to attach a syringe heated to keep the chocolate melted whilst printing.

description.text:
BLTouch Mount for the Tevo Black Widow..

Requires 2 4mm bolts and nuts for mounting.
2 Small self taping screws for mounting the BLtouch

Marlin Config-
Start with the marlin files for Bltouch on the Facebook group's files page.
Update with the following:
X_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER 41 // X offset: -left +right [of the nozzle]
Y_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER 3 // Y offset: -front +behind [the nozzle]
Z_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER -1.6 // Z offset: -below +above [the nozzle]

I also use the following tool to make sure my BLTouch is the proper distance from the bed.
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1538742

Calibration
These instructions are written to explain how to calibrate using
a computer connected through the USB port to your printer.
This process also assumes that the EEPROM has been enabled in Marlin.
From the command window of Repetier Host or Simplify3D etc enter the following:
M851 ; note the number
M851 Z0 ; set the offset to zero
G28
G1 Z0
The LCD display should show Z =0

From the display go to the Menu then Prepare/Move axis/0.1mm/Move Z
Now move the Z axis slowly down until the nozzle is the right distance from the build plate
(folded piece of paper or thin card).

*Note the Z axis value on the display it should be something like -1.5

M851 Z-1.5 ; to set the offset you got in the previous step.

M500 ; Stores the values in EEPROM so that it is not reset when you power the printer off and on.

That's it - you are ready to print.

If you find that you need to increase or decrease the gap then do:
M851 Z-1.4 ; this would make the gap bigger
or
M851 Z-1.6 ; this would make the gap smaller

M500 ; to save the value to EEPROM

(remember the -1.4, -1.5 and -1.6 are just examples , yours will be different)

title: Da Vinci 1.0 AiO MK8 Conversion for PETG

description.text:
Wanted to get the Da Vinci to print more exotic filaments. What a pain in the @33!!! Well I have found a simple setup that works for PLA and PETG. I have successfully printed PETG over the last month with no problems. Going to start trying higher print quality now that I have cleaned up the look of the cables. The video is of the circuit board plate mount being printed. I am using Simplify3D and happy so far, the new update 3.0? is kind of glitchy though. Put a little double stick tape under the circuit board to hold it down. Then added small section of filament into the filament cartridge so the alarm won't go off. :)

I have also moved to Kapton tape for the bed. Haven't used anything else since.

Parts needed:
1x MK8 Extruder
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01F6LW4MO/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o07_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

1x Extruder Tube:
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01I4ZQU6U/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o01_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

Heatsink:
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B016W7IZLK/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o02_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

Heated Ends:
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00L4UXQ42/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o05_s01?ie=UTF8&psc=1

Heated Block:
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B0188OLMNS/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o05_s02?ie=UTF8&psc=1

2x Long Metric bolts:
M3x25 mm bolt for extruder and heat sink.
https://www.amazon.com/AXA120-Socket-Button-10-Piece-M3x25mm/dp/B0035XQY4U/ref=sr_1_6?ie=UTF8&qid=1471312056&sr=8-6&keywords=m3x25+mm

2x Cable Chain:
https://www.amazon.com/Black-Plastic-Chain-Carrier-Router/dp/B00880AVL2/ref=sr_1_1?s=hi&ie=UTF8&qid=1471300420&sr=1-1&keywords=cable+chain

Kapton Tape:
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00U1X3XLY/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o02_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

I bought 100K Ohm Thermistors just incase. Good thing as I needed them. I soldered my own up and used these. You may want to find some premade.
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00UFBIRVI/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o05_s02?ie=UTF8&psc=1

Quick and easy change out. Also allows for quick return to original parts. The toughest part is taking the original pulley off the stepper motor, but even that wasn't difficult. Use a pulley puller or a butane torch with pliers to remove. A quick google search will show you what I mean. If this sounds to difficult you can also just order another stepper motor.

As for under the bed I used some old Ink Jet printer insulation covered in Kapton tape to keep the underside insulated. Pre-heating is fast and stays level during printing. The fan cools everything down for little time in between prints.

Hope someone can get something out of this. Thanks

I DO NOT TAKE ANY RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE MODS YOU DO TO YOUR MACHINE.

Added a PDF file of the starting points for my PETG configuration in Simplify3D. Some may not agree with it but it works for me. The biggest thing is the first layer. It must lay like tooth paste. If you see it smashing just turn the adjusters 1 turn then try again.

Food Safety

IF I UNDERSTAND CORRECTLY, PLA plastic in and of itself is food safe. The only issue is that it's hard to get all food particle out of all the nooks and crannies created during the printing process. After printing, I sanded the inside, progressing to 220 grit sandpaper. The upper part of the funnel was made octagonal just to make the sanding easier.

DO YOUR OWN RESEARCH ON FOOD SAFETY. I MAKE NO REPRESENTATIONS AS TO THE APPROPRIATENESS OF THIS DESIGN OR 3D PRINTING IN GENERAL FOR USE IN FOOD PREPARATION UTENSILS.

I've found that this object printed in PLA is NOT bottom-rack dishwasher safe. It's just barely top-rack safe. :(

I've included the OpenSCAD file for the funnel. You might want to edit the following parameters at the top of the file:

  • wall - The wall thickness of pretty much every element.
  • topOutDia & topHt - the diameter and height of the top of the funnel. I picked fairly small numbers to limit the amount of time and plastic it took to the print my funnel.
  • fn3 - the number of sides of the upper part of the funnel. fn3=8 makes it octagonal.
  • fn2 - the number of sides on the middle "skirt". Again, 8 is octagonal.

description.text:
My project is to allow the base Prusa i3 to be multi tools with minimum modifications and optimized printables components.
Originally designed for the Prusa i3 P802M/MA... 4mm thick 3D Printers's bed but, can fit on others too !

To be able to restrain a material on the printer bed, we need a fixation system.

The challenge with Prusa i3 3D printer is that there isn't a lot of space around the moving bed to fit any system.
So, if one wants to use his printer as a CNC plotter, miller, a laser engraver or just to extrude filament on another material and/or with more height on the bed, you will need stable, thight and precise fixation.
BlockOnBed is born !

Optimized to be printable in 20 cm 20 cm 20 cm area.
Designed to be just outside the 20 cm 20 cm 20 cm so there is no lost of print/work surface.
Ruler in centimeter at bed level.

The fixations are composed with 2 pieces : 1 still and 1 mobile inserted in the guides above the new material lying on the printer bed. Then theses 2 pieces are secured tight with a set of screw and nuts (5mm or/and 3mm).
